===subject:re: L Bowie;Chapter 10 Discussion
===from:Chris Schmidt
===date:Sun Apr  6 11:37:20 2003
===message:
 <p>I think multiculturalism is a double edged sword. On one hand, you give minorities, who typicly occupy the bottom rungs of society, a sense of identity and purpose that helps give them the pride and drive necessary to rise out of a cycle of poverty. That in turns helps the whole of society and helps bring races and ethnic groups closer to equality and evenutaly coexistance and cohabitation. In a racialy and ethnicly diverse country like the US, uniting factions is a urgent goal to preserve national unity.</p>
<p>On the other hand there is a dark side to multiculturalism which does not lead to unity or peacefull coexistance. Groups like the Black Panthers exhibited the failings of the multicultural movement in America. These groups never had a reasonable political agenda and were merely outlets for hate and frustration.</p>
<p>One coul argue that people are better off because of  these movements. They show how violent devisive organizations can spin off of legitimate political movements.</p>
=========yorg=========
